RigidBody2D

RigidBody2D moves with physics

The RigidBody2D node lets you move objects using physics with minimal coding required. You apply forces, impulses, and torque to move objects in your scene.

RigidBody2D handles gravity and collisions out of the box, so you get up and running with minimal coding.

This is in contrast to a KinematicBody2D, which you move and rotate by hand. Choosing between these two is a tradeoff between precise controls and automated physics.

RigidBody2D is incredibly versatile. You can use it for bouncing grenades, push-able blocks, destructible terrain, and much more.

In this guide, you will learn:

  • How to create top-down and side-scrolling player controllers with RigidBody2D.
  • How to push bodies with forces in an explosion.
  • How to set up a scene to simulate gravity and collisions.
  • How to change the mode of a RigidBody2D for breaking a ship into debris with physics.

Setting up a RigidBody2D

In Godot, physics nodes need a collision shape or polygon as a child to define their collider.

This is true of Area2D, KinematicBody2D, StaticBody2D, and in our case, RigidBody2D.

The collision shape lets them figure out when they are touching or overlapping other bodies.

You need three components for a RigidBody2D to work:

  1. The RigidBody2D node itself, which will handle forces applied to itself.
  2. One or more CollisionShape2D or CollisionPolygon2D that define the polygon(s) of the RigidBody2D.
  3. Each collision shape has a shape resource associated with them (probably a RectangleShape2D or a CircleShape2D, but it could also be another Shape2D), while the collision polygon has an array of points.

You will also want to add either a texture or a polygon to represent the RigidBody2D. Standard options for that are Sprite, AnimatedSprite, or Polygon2D.

You can also enable Visible Collision Shapes in the Debug dropdown menu to see the colliders when testing the game.

RigidBody2D key features

The RigidBody2D has many properties that control how it should react to forces. A lot of your setup will involve tweaking its properties in the editor.

Forces and impulses

You control motion on rigid bodies with add_force() and add_impulse():

  • add_force() registers a force that continuously applies to the body, every frame. Think of something like an engine propelling a ship forward or gravity pulling a body down (note the engine applies gravity to rigid bodies by default).
  • add_impulse() helps you register impacts: it’s a force applied only once upon calling the function. For example, the impact of an explosion or a projectile hitting something.

Technically, you could apply the same impulse every frame with a time delta to achieve the same effect as add_force(). However, it requires more code and care, which is why both functions exist.

Applying forces and impulses

You can apply a force with the add_central_force() and add_force() methods.

A central force only moves a body from its center of mass while add_force() lets you move the body from any local position.

If you offset the force from its center of mass with add_force(), the node may rotate.

To apply an impulse, you want to call apply_central_impulse() or apply_impulse(). They work the same as force-related methods, except they only apply a one-time impulse.

Note: Applying impulses every frame will make your force framerate-dependent. If the player’s framerate goes down, your bodies’ motions will slow down too.

That’s why you only want to use those methods for one-time impulses, like explosions.

Alternatively, you can multiply your impulse by the time since the last physics update when overriding the _integrate_forces() virtual method. The function provides a state.step value, the time interval between two physics ticks.

You’ll see below how we use state.step in concrete use cases.

Overriding forces

There are some cases when you want to cancel out or manage the overall force moving your body by yourself.

Imagine an enemy casts a fireball at you, and you use a spell to grab it in mid-air and throw it back at them.

To reset forces, you can change the value of the applied_force property.

extends RigidBody2D

func cancel_forces() -> void:
    applied_force = Vector2.ZERO

Finally, note the body’s Mass property affects how forces work. The higher the Mass, the more force you need to move.

Applying rotational forces

While the add_force() and apply_impulse() methods can cause a body to rotate on top of moving, you may want only to apply a rotational force at times, also called torque.

You can use that to make a wheel turn, for instance.

To apply constant torque, use the add_torque() method. For a one-time rotational impulse, you’ll use apply_torque_impulse() instead.

The Inertia property of a RigidBody2D is to torque what Mass is to forces: the higher the Inertia, the more torque it takes to rotate the body.

Forces are complex and warrant experimenting with. They are designed to interact with each other and joined to create complex behaviors.

Integrating forces

Unlike with other physics nodes, you don’t want to directly change the position of a RigidBody2D inside _physics_process(). As the physics engine applies forces to it, you need to be careful when modifying the body’s state manually.

To do so, you want to override and use the _integrate_forces() virtual function. This lets all the forces acting on a body combine properly with changes in linear_velocity.

The function contains a Physics2DDirectBodyState object called state, which includes information on the state of your rigid body. You can call functions on this object or access variables like linear_velocity to determine how fast the body is moving.

Accessing properties using this state ensures they are up to date following collisions, forces and impulses.

You’ll see some examples in this guide.

The node’s four modes

A RigidBody2D has four modes that change its general behavior:

  • By default, it uses the Rigid mode. In this mode, the body falls under the effect of and pushes other bodies it collides with.
  • The Static mode makes your RigidBody2D completely stationary. It is useful when enabling and disabling doors, locking objects in place.
  • The Character mode is ideal for player characters. It behaves similarly to rigid mode but won’t rotate on its own. This ensures a player’s character remains upright.
  • Finally, Kinematic is a helpful mode for manually making changes to a body. This mode makes the RigidBody2D work similarly to a KinematicBody2D: it doesn’t integrate forces, and you have to change its position manually. Use it to take manual control over a character or in cases where you need to teleport the body to a precise location.

You can control the active mode using the node’s Mode property.

You can switch mode on the fly depending on your needs. For instance, a character can go from the Character mode to Rigid when dying, causing it to get pushed around by other bodies.

Mass, weight, and gravity scale

Three properties greatly affect how a RigidBody2D moves:

  1. Mass represents how massive the object is.
    • The higher the value, the more force you need to move it.
    • On the other hand, setting it to a low number makes an object easy to knock about.
    • The body’s center of mass is at the node’s origin.
  2. Weight is Mass multiplied by the Default Gravity, so updating the Mass updates its Weight in turn.
  3. The Default Gravity is a project-wide setting.
    • The physics engine applies it to every RigidBody2D to make them move down towards the ground.
    • You can change it by going to Project Settings -> Physics -> 2D -> Default Gravity.

Godot’s default gravity is low, set to 9.8.

If you want objects to fall faster, you will need to increase this in project settings. You can also increase the gravity scales on your RigidBody2D itself.

Note that Mass and Weight do not affect the speed at which an object falls.

This is the same as the real world: all objects fall at the same speed. See the hammer and feather experiment on the Moon.

You either need to increase gravity or apply an extra downwards force to make an object fall faster. We’ll see how to apply forces in the examples below.

Reporting contacts

RigidBody2D has four convenient signals to detect and react when it hit something.

The main two are body_entered and body_exited. They are and work similarly to Area2D’s signals: when a collision happens, the callback tells you what you hit.

You can use them to trigger an explosion when touching a mine, to inflict damage, and more.

However, by default, rigid bodies don’t report collisions and points of contact for performance reasons.

The collisions happen; the node just won’t emit signals.

If you want the node to emit these signals, there are two steps:

  1. Turn on Contact Monitor to turn on collision reports.
  2. Increase Contacts Reported to the number of contacts you want to pay attention to. Once the node emitted this number of signals, it will ignore the rest in that frame.

As a rule of thumb, you can set contacts reported relatively high if you are dealing with one object.

However, if you have many objects detecting collisions, you want to limit the reported contacts for performance.

You’ll have to play with the Contacts Reported property in your game to see what works for you.

Physics materials

Physics materials let you fine-tune how forces affect rigid bodies.

You can save a PhysicsMaterial as a resource and assign it to any RigidBody2D’s Physics Material Override to reuse it.

The properties you can control are Friction, Rough, Bounce, and Absorbent:

  • Friction determines how much an object slows when colliding with another. It can be useful to set Friction low on a player character, or the player will move slower on the floor due to gravity.
  • Rough is a toggle that determines how bodies with different frictions interact. If a body is rough, both colliding bodies will use the highest friction. In short, this lets you slow down objects that collide with this body.
  • Bounce determines how much momentum is lost in a collision. With 0 bounce, an object will stop immediately. A bounce of 1.0 means the body will change direction instead of losing momentum. Think of a basketball hitting the floor versus wet tissue paper.
  • Absorbent is a toggle that determines how bodies with different bounce interact. The bounciness of the absorbent body is subtracted from the colliding body. In short, a bouncy object colliding with an absorbent body will bounce less.

How to use a RigidBody2d in practice

Making a top-down player controller

If you want the player to get knocked about by the environment, you should consider a RigidBody2D. You can simulate collisions very easily at the cost of having less control of the player compared to a KinematicBody2D.

In this example, we’ll make a ship that moves smoothly in space with only a few lines of code. This approach leads to nice arcade controls with some drag.

For this kind of controller, you generally want control over how the character rotates. You can set the RigidBody2D’s Mode to Character to do so.

For the collision shape, circles and rectangles tend to work best: they’re easiest for the player to feel and understand intuitively.

In this demo, we used a circle for collisions.

To make the character’s control feel tight, you can play with Linear -> Damp and set it to a value greater than 1.0. It makes the body slow down automatically when you don’t apply forces and smoothly come to a stop. The higher the value, the faster it stops.

To move the character, we can directly set the force that moves it every frame.

export var move_force_amplitude := 6000.0

func _physics_process(delta: float) -> void:
    # We get the player's input direction as a 2D vector.
    var direction := Vector2(
        Input.get_action_strength("move_right") - Input.get_action_strength("move_left"),
        Input.get_action_strength("move_down") - Input.get_action_strength("move_up")
    ).normalized()

    # We directly update the total applied forces to the node.
    # If the player presses a direction key, we apply a force to the ship.
    # If the player does not press in any direction, the multiplication resets
    # the force to Vector2(0, 0), letting friction slow down the ship.
    applied_force = direction * move_force_amplitude
    # We rotate the sprite to face the movement direction.
    _sprite.rotation = linear_velocity.angle() + PI / 2

Now, the player can move around with acceleration and drag. The best part is that any bodies you collide with will have impulses applied to them.

Note that setting applied_force only works in cases like this ship, where you don’t use add_force() to apply a constant thrust to the object. Setting the applied_force variable directly overwrites any other forces.

Making a side-scrolling player controller

Many games take advantage of rigid player characters with physics. For example, a pinball machine, a bird in Angry Birds, and the worms in Worms.

Rigid physics are ideal for games where you want to crash into lots of objects in your world.

Here, you’ll see how to create a side-scrolling game character that walks and jumps with a RigidBody2D and only a few lines of code.

Making a player with a RigidBody2D is convenient as Godot handles gravity automatically. We couldn’t recommend it for all platformers, but using a RigidBody2D over a KinematicBody2D can work well for some action games like Scribblenauts and Mount Your Friends.

You can use a RigidBody2D in the Character mode for a platform game controller.

In this example, we use a Physics Material Override without any friction to stop gravity slowing your movement down as the physics engine pushes you into the floor.

Contacts Reported determines how many collisions Godot will pay attention to per frame. If this number isn’t high enough, we can miss collisions with the floor. Yet, we need them to know that the character is on the floor and can jump.

For a side-scrolling character in a game with curved terrain or slopes, you can set this number to at least 3 or 4.

You can then use RigidBody2D._integrate_forces() to apply impulses or forces based on the player’s inputs.

export var speed := 6000.0
export var jump := 100000.0

func _integrate_forces(state: Physics2DDirectBodyState) -> void:
    # we calculate the player's horizontal direction.
    var direction := Input.get_action_strength("ui_right") - Input.get_action_strength("ui_left")

    # If the player is on the floor and they pressed the jump button add a jump
    # impulse.
    # See is_on_floor() below.
    if is_on_floor(state) and Input.is_action_pressed("shoot"):
        apply_central_impulse(Vector2.UP * jump * state.step)

    # We apply a horizontal force based on the input direction.
    apply_central_impulse(Vector2.RIGHT * direction * speed * state.step)

As RigidBody2D doesn’t have a convenient is_on_floor() function, unlike KinematicBody2D, we can code it ourselves.

func is_on_floor(state: Physics2DDirectBodyState) -> bool:
    # We check every collision reported. This depends on the contacts_reported
    # property and points of contact with the world.
    for contact in state.get_contact_count():
        # To know if we're on the floor, we check the collision normal. If the
        # normal vector roughly points up, we consider we're on the floor.
        var contact_normal := state.get_contact_local_normal(contact)
        # The vector dot product returns a value greater than 0 when two vectors
        # point in the same direction.
        # More precisely, the operation returns 0 when two vectors are
        # perpendicular and 1 when they're parallel.
        if contact_normal.dot(Vector2.UP) > 0.5:
            return true
    return false

Make an explosion with forces

When making an explosion, you want objects and rubble to blast away from the origin. Rigid bodies are great for this as you can have the explosion apply an impulse to the objects in the blast radius.

Your scene will have a lot more life if the world reacts to big forces like explosions. Using rigid bodies for the objects you want to send flying will let you dynamically apply forces to them.

In this example, we created an explosion animation attached to a rocket. The rocket itself is a RigidBody2D. With the Contacts Reported set to 1, we detect when it collides with something and make it explode in reaction.

We handle the explosion with an animation.

The animation:

  • Hides some sprites and particles.
  • Plays the Explosion particle system by calling the Particles2D.restart() built-in method.
  • Changes the Rocket’s Mode to Static so it stops moving.
  • Scales a halo circle up over time. This halo relies on a shader.

In the rocket’s code, we connect the body_entered to know when a collision occurred. And when it does, we call an explode() method.

class_name Rocket
extends RigidBody2D

## The maximum impulse we apply to bodies within the blast radius.
const BLAST_IMPULSE := 1500.0

onready var _animation_player: AnimationPlayer = $AnimationPlayer


func _ready() -> void:
    # We use the body_entered signal to detect when the rocket collides with
    # something.
    # When it does, we make it explode directly.
    connect("body_entered", self, "_on_body_entered")


func explode() -> void:
    # We first play the explode animation.
    _animation_player.play("explode")
    # We then get all bodies in the explosion area and loop over each.
    var colliders := _explosion_area.get_overlapping_bodies()
    for body in colliders:
        # If we detect a RigidBody2D, we can apply an impulse from the center of
        # the explosion to blast it outward.
        if body is RigidBody2D:
            var direction := global_position.direction_to(body.global_position)
            body.apply_central_impulse(BLAST_IMPULSE * direction)


func _on_body_entered(_body: Node) -> void:
    explode()

When the rocket touches a wall or another ship, it explodes, pushing everything away from it.

Creating structures that collapse and fall over

Many games will want objects that react to physics. Be it boxes you push around, pressure plates, destructible terrain, or walls collapsing. Think of something like Angry Birds.

Here, we cover the example of a scene with a tower that you can knock over with a cannonball.

Clicking sends a projectile flying. When it touches the tower with the right trajectory, it causes it to fall apart.

With RigidBody2D, you get that almost for free. You just need both your projectile (the cannonball) and the structure to destroy to use rigid bodies.

You can set the starting velocity for a projectile with its linear_velocity property. Then, you can tweak other physics properties on towers to get the behavior you want.

Here’s how you can code the projectile itself. A separate player-controlled weapon instantiates the projectile, causing it to fire.

# The weapon that instances the cannonball sets this direction when instancing it.
var direction := Vector2.RIGHT

func _ready() -> void:
    # Making the projectile toplevel makes it move independently from its
    # parent.
    set_as_toplevel(true)
    # We give our projectile an initial velocity in the direction we fire it.
    linear_velocity = 1500 * direction
    look_at(direction)

For the structure, you want to create individual rigid bodies with a collision shape and place them in the editor.

These objects have many properties that let you fine-tune their behavior:

  • The higher their Mass, the more velocity the cannonball will need to knock them down.
  • If you want your bodies to fall faster, you can increase their Gravity Scale or add an applied force downwards via code.

For the cannonball, you can add a PhysicsMaterial to get access to more properties, such as Bounce and Friction.

We set our cannonball to have a Bounce of 0.5 to bounce on the structure upon hitting it.

If your objects are rolling around too much, increase their Angular Damping property. This is very helpful for circular bodies that tend to rotate easily.

Turning bodies into debris with the mode property

There are many objects you might want to have explode into tiny pieces and collide with physics. Examples include shattered glass, a splintering crate, or an enemy exploding into giblets.

Here, we have a ship explode into its core components on death, drift around the void of space and collide with the environment.

The ship is player-controlled until it takes too much damage and breaks apart. When that happens, we take control away from the player and send debris flying.

To do so, we have three rigid bodies for the main parts of the hull. By default, we set their Mode to Kinematic so they only follow the ship.

When the ship explodes, changing their Mode to Rigid allows us to give them an impulse to simulate them exploding out from the center.

To keep the player-controlled ship locked in place, when it dies, we change its mode to RigidBody2D.MODE_KINEMATIC.

We also change our original ship to Kinematic mode to stop it from moving. If your body and its fragments overlap, keep them in separate collision layers or deactivate the body’s collision shapes.

Here’s the code we use when the ship explodes.

onready var _sprite := $Sprite

# Called when the ship took too much damage.
func explode() -> void:
    # We hide the main ship's sprite. In the loop below, we made the debris
    # visible.
    _sprite.visible = false
    # We loop over all children. If they are rigid bodies, we give them an
    # impulse.
    for child in get_children():
        if child is RigidBody2D:
            # We make our components visible and rigid so they move under the
            # effect of physics.
            child.visible = true
            child.mode = MODE_RIGID
            # We apply an impulse in a random direction.
            child.apply_central_impulse(1000 * Vector2(rand_range(-1, 1), rand_range(-1, 1)))
    # Finally, we disable movement for our ship.
    mode = MODE_KINEMATIC

Exploding polygons with code using Delaunay triangulation

There are many cases where you may want the shrapnel from your explosions to be in random shapes, or you want to avoid the legwork of manually creating giblets and chunks of spaceship hull.

With the clever application of polygons, you can dynamically split your rigid bodies into shapes with just code using Delaunay Triangulation!

This function takes a polygon and returns a list of triangles that makes up that polygon. You can read a little more in the official Geometry class documentation, or even the wikipedia page on Delaunay triangulation to dig deeper into the topic.

Note: This doesn’t generate new points; the function will return the indices of the points from your original polygon.

To make our polygon break into more pieces, we can add extra internal vertices.

For our example, we have asteroids exploding when the player clicks on them. So we will add the point where the player clicked as an extra vertex for more variety in our explosion.

We need two scenes to make this setup work: a RigidBody2D with a CollisionPolygon and a Polygon2D for the texture. This is the base for our base asteroid.

We then need another scene with the same structure to make the fragments of our asteroid.

We need to use a CollisionPolygon2D rather than a CollisionShape2D, to use the triangulate_delaunay_2d() function.

In our asteroid, we need to define a packed scene to hold the asteroid fragment scene, and we need access to our two polygons.

export var _asteroid_fragment_scene: PackedScene

onready var _collision_polygon: CollisionPolygon2D = $CollisionPolygon2D
onready var _particles: Particles2D = $Particles2D
onready var _polygon: Polygon2D = $Polygon2D

Now, we can trigger our explosion with clicks by using the _input_event() virtual function and checking for clicks defined in our input map.

func _input_event(_viewport: Object, event: InputEvent, _shape_idx: int) -> void:
    if event.is_action_pressed("click"):
        explode(get_local_mouse_position())

Now we have the nuts and bolts of the explosion, using Delaunay triangulation.

We start by saving the polygon we want to explode. Once this is saved, we can add the origin of our explosion (where we clicked) to the polygon.

We can pass this polygon into the triangulate_delaunay_2d() function from the Geometry class. This function will return a PoolIntArray, of indices from our original polygon.

Every three indices make up a triangle. We can convert this data structure to a simple array using the Array() function to make it easier to handle.

We will need two for loops to handle this array, one iterating every three indices over each triangle and an interior loop over the three points in that triangle.

We will use the optional third parameter of the range function step to loop over each triangle.

range(0, delaunay_pointers.size(), 3)

This setup generates an array of points in the delaunay_pointers array, increasing in increments of 3, like so:

[0, 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 21, 24]

Each of these indices will be the first point of each of our triangles.

The second will loop over the points in the triangle by taking advantage of the slice() function.

This function will return the values in an array between two indices to get just the points of our triangle.

delaunay_pointers.slice(pointer, pointer + 2)

We can create a new PoolVector2Array and save each point from the triangle into that to get our new polygon.

As mentioned earlier, to get the position of the point, we need to take the Delaunay index we have and use that to get the position from our original polygon like so:

delaunay_triangle.append(original_polygon[point])

We can wrap this up by instancing an asteroid shard scene and passing it the triangle polygon we just created.

## Split the asteroid polygon into smaller triangles and create
## AsteroidFragment instances.
func explode(origin: Vector2) -> void:
    var original_polygon = _polygon.polygon
    # Add an extra point to shatter at the point of impact. Adds destruction variation.
    original_polygon.append(origin)

    # Split the polygon into triangles using delaunay triangulation.
    # triangulate_delaunay_2d() returns a re-ordered list of indices (or
    # pointers) which can be used to get several triangles out of a polygon's
    # Vector2 points.
    var delaunay_pointers = Array(Geometry.triangulate_delaunay_2d(original_polygon))
    # Repeat for every group of three pointers.
    for pointer in range(0, delaunay_pointers.size(), 3):
        # Create a new triangle used for the fragment.
        var delaunay_triangle = PoolVector2Array()
        # Cycle through each of the three points that make up the triangle.
        for point in delaunay_pointers.slice(pointer, pointer + 2):
            # Add a Vector2 point from the original polygon to the new triangle.
            delaunay_triangle.append(original_polygon[point])
        # Create an asteroid fragment from the new triangle, using the same texture.
        var fragment = _asteroid_fragment_scene.instance()
        fragment.setup(delaunay_triangle, _polygon.texture)
        add_child(fragment)

The asteroid fragment doesn’t need to do a lot. Give that polygon to its CollisionPolygon and Polygon2D and launch itself in a random direction, and we’re done!

## Maximum force to shoot the fragment outward.
const MAX_FORCE := 666
## Minimum force to shoot the fragment outward.
const MIN_FORCE := 333

onready var _collision_polygon: CollisionPolygon2D = $CollisionPolygon2D
onready var _polygon: Polygon2D = $Polygon2D


## Gives the fragment its shape and appearance, sets a random velocity and
## direction.
func setup(polygon: PoolVector2Array, texture: Texture) -> void:
    # We call function before adding this node to the scene tree.
    yield(self, "ready")
    randomize()
    _collision_polygon.polygon = polygon
    _polygon.polygon = polygon
    _polygon.texture = texture
    linear_velocity = (
        rand_range(MIN_FORCE, MAX_FORCE)
        * Vector2.UP.rotated(rand_range(0, TAU))
    )

Your questions

When should I use a RigidBody2D over a KinematicBody2D?

Rigid bodies are great for an awful lot of things: ropes, fluids, traps, jump pads, motors, simple enemies, and much more.

Consider using a rigid body if your player exerts forces on or is forced by other bodies. In that case, you should consider using a rigid body for your player character.

They are also especially popular for mobile games like Cut the Rope and Angry Birds, as you can have lots happening with simple inputs. The concept of simple rules causing complex behaviors is also known as emergent gameplay.

How can I make something float?

Using Gravity Scale, you can make any object float with ease. The Gravity Scale is a multiplier for the default gravity applied to a body. You can increase it to make a body fall faster.

Setting Gravity Scale to 0.0 will make an object float in place as no gravity acts on the body. You can take this a step further and put the Gravity Scale to -1.0.

A negative Gravity Scale will make an object fall upwards instead of falling to the ground and create objects like balloons. As this negative gravity exerts a force, you can use a pin joint to exert an upwards force on another body.

An alternative approach is to set the applied force of the balloon to be upwards and powerful enough to overcome the body’s gravity.

What is sleeping?

When a body is asleep, it acts as a static body. Being asleep means the _integrate_forces() function will not run until a collision or code applies a force. Sleeping is excellent for reducing function calls if you have many rigid bodies.

The Can Sleep and Sleeping properties determine when a RigidBody2D goes to sleep. You can set the Sleeping property manually; it tells us if the body is currently asleep. The Can Sleep property tells us if the physics engine can automatically update the value of Sleeping after a duration at rest with no active forces.

The Can Sleep property updates Sleeping with the physics engine. Rigid bodies have the sleeping_state_changed signal for notifying you when the sleeping state of a body has changed.

Note: A body set to Character mode will never go to sleep automatically, but you can still set it manually.

Can I scale my rigid body?

Don’t scale your rigid bodies! Instead, change the size of the shape directly.

Collision shapes easily break when you change their scale dynamically. Changing the scale of a physics body doesn’t apply any forces and will lead to unexpected behavior.

If you want to change the scale of a PhysicsBody2D, you should access the size values of your shape directly.

Another option is to create multiple collision shapes for a body and disable those not at the current size, enabling shapes and scaling the sprites separately.

There is room for unexpected behavior when changing the size of a body in too small a space. It is worth using one or more RayCast2D to detect if your body has enough space to expand.

How can I figure out if a body will have a collision?

The test_motion() function returns true if a collision would occur after moving a given distance. The function takes a few optional parameters; in the simplest case, you should provide a Vector2 indicating how you want the body to move.

The test_motion() function has three optional parameters:

  1. infinite_inertia will make your collision ignore rigid bodies if set to true unless they are in static mode.
  2. margin determines the size of shapes involved in collision detection. The larger this is, the less accurate the tested motion will be, but your calculation will be less performance intensive.
  3. result is a Physics2DTestMotionResult. You can instance this object before passing it in. The function will update the result to contain details about any potential collisions. For example, it gives you the collision point, normal, and a reference to the colliding body.
var velocity := Vector2(100.0, 0.0)
# We need to define this motion result class to get information extra data back from the test_motion() function.
var motion_result := Physics2DTestMotionResult.new()
var will_collide := test_motion(velocity, true, 0.08, motion_result)
# printt() prints each argument separated by a tab character ("\t"), spacing them out.
printt(motion_result.motion_remainder, motion_result.collision_point)
